<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-159-120 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 710 547</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 6 1991 v25 n18 p88(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Group urges end of encryption export ban. (includes relatedarticle on how ban affected HDC Computer Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer firms told the US Department of Commerce Computer SystemsTechnical Advisory Committee that the ban on export of computerproducts that encrypt data is not working, and inhibits USmanufacturers' ability to compete internationally.andP;  Further, theban does not prevent overseas customers from encryptinginformation the US government would like to know about.andO;Manufacturers presently develop and support two versions ofproducts.andP;  One with encryption capabilities is releaseddomestically, and another without such capabilities is exported.andO;The committee itself recommends that mass-produced software shouldbe completely free of export controls, whether it contains dataencryption or not.andP;  The recommendation must be approved by theDepartments of Commerce, State and Defense.andP;  The National SecurityCouncil also may have a say in the decision.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of Commerce. Computer Systems TechnicalAdvisory CommitteeExportInternational TradeGovernment RegulationEncryption.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>